TI Energy-efficient photonic neural networks for high-speed AI computation
SO JOURNAL OF OPTICS-INDIA
LA English
DT Article; Early Access
DE Photonic neural networks; Energy; Mach-Zehnder interferometer
AB Photonic Neural Networks (PNNs) are an innovative computational paradigm that leverages the speed and efficiency of light to perform neural network operations. By utilizing components like lasers, Mach-Zehnder Interferometers (MZIs), and optical waveguides, PNNs can achieve computation speeds in the terahertz (THz) range, far exceeding the gigahertz (GHz) speeds of traditional electronic neural networks. This speed advantage is coupled with exceptional energy efficiency, as PNNs eliminate energy-intensive electrical-to-optical conversions and reduce resistive losses, making them ideal for large-scale applications such as data centers.In a 4-neuron PNN, for instance, an input power vector (1, 0.8, 0.6, 0.4) represents varying light intensities fed into the system. The weights matrix, determined randomly, influences phase shifts in the MZIs, ranging from 0 to pi radians. The output power is governed by the cosine-squared function of these phase shifts, leading to dynamic variations in the output. For example, neuron 1's output power decreases from 1.0 to 0.5, while neuron 3 experiences significant amplification, with output power rising from 0.6 to 2.2. Each neuron consumes only 0.1 picojoules (pJ), resulting in a total energy consumption of 0.4 pJ for the entire network. These results demonstrate PNNs' ability to process optical signals with remarkable efficiency, offering both lower energy consumption and faster speeds compared to electronic neural networks. This makes PNNs a promising solution for developing energy-efficient, high-speed AI hardware, capable of meeting the growing demands of modern computational tasks. By combining the advantages of light-based computation with the scalability of neural networks, PNNs pave the way for transformative advancements in artificial intelligence and machine learning, enabling faster and more sustainable computing solutions for the future.
