ID GOOS-HANCHEN SHIFTS; LIGHT
AB In this work, we propose a novel approach to regulate the photonic spin Hall effect (PSHE) by inserting a thin chiral layer between parity-time (PT)-symmetric bilayers. By controlling the presence or absence of this chiral layer and varying its parameters, we analyze the effect of this quasi-PT-symmetric structure on PSHE. Our results demonstrate that the PT-symmetric bilayer significantly influences the quasi-exceptional points (quasi-EPs), and the thin chiral layer is essential for the dynamic regulation of the transverse shift (TS) and longitudinal shift (LS). Building on these findings, we propose a feasible scheme for optical signal encoding and optical logic gates based on PSHE, and demonstrate how to construct a complete optical logic gate encryption system. These findings open up new possibilities for optical signal encryption and the practical application of tunable optoelectronic devices.
