AB The development of AI based on neural networks has been remarkable, and AI is now widely used for various tasks. High-precision AI models, often surpassing human capabilities, require an enormous number of parameters, raising concerns about the cost and energy consumption of the hardware used for both training and inference. As a potential solution, optical neural networks (ONNs) that implement neural networks using light propagation and diffraction have attracted significant attention due to their high processing speed and low power consumption.
   In line with the progression of image processing tasks in deep learning using convolutional neural networks (CNNs)-from image classification to object detection-we aim to advance object detection using ONNs. In this report, we prepared the dataset comprising four types of mass-produced industrial products and investigated the feasibility of multi-class object detection with ONNs through numerical analysis and experimental validation. Our results demonstrate that 4-class object detection was numerically achieved, and 2-class object detection was experimentally verified using the optical processor we developed. Additionally, our analysis indicates the potential for increasing the number of detection classes and detecting more complex shapes. These findings demonstrate that multi-class object detection with ONNs is feasible, opening up new possibilities for optical neural network-based image processing technologies.
